      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Introduction</h3>We learned that when it is not possible to count using just our fingers, we can ask for help from other people. However, sometimes this is still not enough (<htcite0>).</p><p><table class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"2\">First person</th><th colspan=\"2\">Second person</th><th colspan=\"2\">Third person</th><th>Fourth person</th></tr>  <tr><td><img id=\"img5900\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img5900', '0%')\" /></td><td><img id=\"img5901\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img5901', '0%')\" /></td><td><img id=\"img5902\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img5902', '0%')\" /></td><td><img id=\"img5903\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img5903', '0%')\" /></td><td><img id=\"img5904\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img5904', '0%')\" /></td><td><img id=\"img5905\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img5905', '0%')\" /></td><td><img id=\"img5906\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img5906', '0%')\" /></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Counting with a team.</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Hands and numbers</b><br />Observing <b>Table 1</b>, how would you replace hands with numbers?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cc8c1467-a6af-4f9c-ba60-ab6df35aba05",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Además de los Dedos",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "07",
                        "day": "23"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "A table showing six hands with all fingers raised and one with only two fingers raised.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_limits",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>The limits</h3>To address the first reflection, we need to discover the limits of our numbers. Using the arrows, verify the possible values we can have with decimal numbers:</p><p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Yupana</i></th><th>Left hand</th><th>Righjt hand</th><th>Hindu-arabic</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"></td><td id=\"tc5f1\"><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg0', '0%')\" id=\"leftHandImg0\" /></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg0', '0%')\" id=\"rightHandImg0\" /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\">&nbsp;</td><td> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></i></td></tr></table>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 2</b>: Representation of a <i>Yupana</i> line according to Poma de Ayala (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>). CSS inspired by source code available on W3Schools (<htcite2>).</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: The limits</b><br />When can we raise all fingers to represent a number?</div></div></center></p><p>The first step to address this reflection is to summarize what we have learned:</p><p><ul><li>When we click the up arrow (green arrow), the numbers increase up to 9.</li><li>When we click the down arrow (blue arrow), the numbers decrease down to 0.</li></ul></p><p>We can conclude that values increase to a maximum limit of nine (9) and decrease to a minimum value of zero (0). These are the limits per position that a number can have in the decimal numerical system, and we must respect them.</p><p>Looking at <b>Table 1</b>, we see that when we needed help counting with our hands, other people stood beside us raising their fingers. We can do the same with numbers, respecting their limits:</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "pp. 355",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "04",
                        "day": "01"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1",
                     "text": "Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman",
                     "page": "pp. 361 - 362",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1615",
                        "month": "02",
                        "day": "13"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "48dd9187-7ecc-4f54-a387-d9ecc2497de3",
                     "text": "W3school",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "01",
                        "day": "27"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2018",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1615",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"yupana1\"><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Second person</th><th colspan=\"2\">First person</th><th>Hindu-Arabic</th><th>Hindu-Arabic</th><th>Arrows</th></tr>  <tr><td><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg2', '0%')\" id=\"leftHandImg2\" /></td><td><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg2', '0%')\" id=\"rightHandImg2\" /></td><td><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg1', '0%')\" id=\"leftHandImg1\" /></td><td><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg1', '0%')\" id=\"rightHandImg1\" /></td><td id=\"tc5f1\"></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"></td><td><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp1\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeDown1\"></i></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 3</b>: The logic of numbers</p><p>The zero (0) represents the concept of emptiness (<htcite0>). Therefore, we do not write zeros on the left side of other numbers, but we can consider that zeros are there. With this in mind, when we reach the maximum (9) in a position, we increase the next value to one, and reset the current position to zero.</p><p>We could continue using the arrows to have numbers greater than nineteen (19), but on this page, we will focus only on these numbers. On the next pages, we will work with larger numbers.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "576e4648-77fa-4a6d-9e51-9459ced964f3",
                     "text": "Musa, Auwalu",
                     "page": "pp. 44, 46 - 48",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "19"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2014",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_mesoamerican",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Extending the numerical system</h3>Besides the decimal system, indigenous peoples created another system, the vigesimal (<htcite0> ; <htcite1> ; <htcite2> ; <htcite3> ; <htcite4>), which has symbols that can be associated with our toes. Below we show the relationship between this system and our fingers:</p><table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"yupana2\"><tr><th>Left hand</th><th>Right hand</th><th>Left foot</th><th>Right foot</th><th>Indigenous</th><th>Hindu-arabic</th></tr> </table><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 4</b>: Hindu-Arabic Numbers and Their Relationship with Our Members.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí, , (ResearchGate)",
                     "page": "pp. 25 - 26",
                     "date_time": {
